The fluorescence response of oPCD probe towards atrazine has been investigated. It is observed that with increase in the concentration of atrazine the emission intensity at 490 nm turns on (Fig. 6
                        a). A linear plot was obtained up to the atrazine concentration 10 nM with a linear correlationship F/F0 = 3.1[ATZ] + 2.78 and regression value of 0.98. Under the optimized conditions at pH 5 the limit of detection (LOD) for atrazine is was found to be 3 pM (Fig. 6b). Such a low detection limit offered by oPCD probe for atrazine is comparable to the lowest detection limit (3.5pM) reported till now (Table 1
                        ) [39–44].

The hydrothermally prepared carbon dots are passivated with dimerized oPD forming amine terminated oPD, which is also evidenced from XPS data. At acidic pH the amine groups are protonated making the fluorophore stable which is indicated by stable luminescence spectrum of oPCD at pH 5 (λex = 420 nm). Under this situation when atrazine is added aggregation is induced via hydrogen bonding (Fig. 7
                        ) with a significant increase in luminescence intensity. Aggregation induced emission (AIE) has been used as a powerful tool in designing fluorescence “turn-on” or “light-up” sensors even at molecular, cellular, and tissue levels which is presented in an excellent review authored by Tang et al. [45]. Although AIE has been extensively investigated in typical luminogens like hexaphenylsilole (HPS), tetraphenylene (TPE) and inorganic metal clustures this important photophysical process has rarely been explored in graphene based luminogens. In a relevant study, Qiu et al. have designed a fluorescence nanosensor for glucose which is based on abnormal enhancement luminescence of boron-doped graphene oxide quantum dots in presence of glucose [46]. Recently, our group has reported the design of glucosamine sensor which works on AIE of B,N,S-doped carbon quantum [47]. In case of atrazine a similar mechanism can be proposed. The presence of atrazine, gives rise to a structurally rigid assembly of oPCD through hydrogen bonding interaction between NH of atrazine and NH3
                        + of oPCD at acidic pH. The structural rigidification restricts intramolecular motions. Restriction of intramolecular motion (RIM) brings about emission enhancement. Intramolecular motion enhances the nonradiative decay rates whereas structural rigidification blocks this radiationless channel directing the relaxation of excitons through radiative channels [48,49]. Thus a very sensitive and enhanced response has been achieved advancing the sensing to a detectable level even at picomolar concentration. Time-resolved fluorescence has shed light on the AIE mechanism.The average life time of the exciton oPCD fluorophore is 7.4 ns. Addition of atrazine even at low concentration (5pM) to oPCD lengthens its PL life time to 7.6 ns (Fig. 8
                        ). Presence of atrazine induces formation of aggregates resulting in a higher population of molecules that decay radiatively.
